ol.li:
30. A method of detecting a disease associated with a mutation in a gene, comprising:
dividing a test sample of alleles of the gene isolated from a patient, to form a plurality of aliquots of alleles of the gene;
amplifying said alleles in said plurality of aliquots to form amplified alleles;
transcribing and translating proteins in vitro using said amplified alleles as transcription templates;
determining size or composition of said proteins, wherein proteins which differ in size or composition from the protein produced by a wild-type allele of the gene indicate a mutation in an amplified allele of the gene which indicates the disease in the patient.

claim.claim-text:
A method of detecting a mutation in a gene, comprising:
dividing a test sample of alleles of the gene isolated from a subject, to form a plurality of aliquots of alleles of the gene wherein said aliquots comprise on average between 0 and 20 alleles prior to amplification;
amplifying said alleles in said plurality of aliquots to form amplified alleles;
transcribing and translating proteins in vitro using said amplified alleles as transcription templates; and
determining size or composition of said proteins, wherein proteins which differ in size or composition from the protein produced by a wild-type allele of the gene indicate a mutation in an amplified allele of the gene.

The method of claim 1 wherein the test sample is:
(i) serum;
(ii) blood;
(iii) plasma;
(iv) semen;
(v) bronchoalveolar lavage; or
(vi) endometrial washing or nipple aspirate.
